div.p:
7. Come we to our ſelves, and as a Reverend and learned Author obſerves;
D. Alleſt.
                we, diverſe of us, have been in our own apprehenſion at deaths door, and have had the proſpect of the other world before our eyes, as it were, and God hath ſaid to us at ſuch a time by his providence, return, return, thou ſhalt not dye, and then our good purpoſes and reſolutions, of dying to our former ſins, die preſently, and we mend into, and live unto our old fins again: And how then ſhould another mans coming from the dead make us repent, when we our ſelves have come, as it were from the dead, and have not repented?
